# WhetherBot / ATLAS Project Rules
# These rules apply to ALL files in this project. Never violate them.

## IDENTITY & CONTEXT
This is a live Kalshi prediction market trading bot called WhetherBot running on:
- Dev machine: Windows C:\Users\Crazy\OneDrive\Desktop\TradingBot\kalshi-weather-bot
- Production machine: Linux Mint ThinkPad at /home/astro/WeatherBot
- Files cannot be transferred directly between machines
- GitHub (https://github.com/5-afk/WeatherBot.git) and Discord are the ONLY reliable communication channels between machines
- The bot trades real money on a live Kalshi account — treat every code change as production-critical

## NEVER DO THESE THINGS
- Never use bare `python` or `python3` in subprocess calls — always use PROJECT_ROOT / "venv" / "bin" / "python"
- Never hardcode city-to-station mappings — always parse settlement station from contract rules_primary text
- Never assume a market is settled based on price ($0.01) or status="closed" — only settle on status="finalized" AND result field populated
- Never place orders to /portfolio/orders — the correct V2 endpoint is /portfolio/events/orders
- Never use status="active" as a query parameter to Kalshi markets list — use status="open"
- Never run discord_commander.py — it is deprecated and conflicts with discord_launcher.py
- Never create duplicate Discord bot instances — exactly ONE bot.run(token) call must exist in the entire codebase
- Never use os.getcwd() for file paths — always use Path(__file__).resolve().parent
- Never use localStorage or sessionStorage in any artifact or dashboard HTML
- Never install packages without --break-system-packages on Linux (pip)
- Never commit .env files — they are gitignored and must be manually maintained on the ThinkPad
- Never use Open-Meteo API — it has been replaced entirely with NWS gridded station forecasts
- Never use hardcoded sigma value of 3.5 — sigma is per-city and per-season from CITY_SIGMA dict
- Never skip the contract validation layer (ContractValidator) before math evaluation
- Never book P&L on status="determined" or status="closed" — only on "finalized"/"settled"
- Never use time.sleep() inside get_ensemble_forecast() — sleeping belongs only in prewarm functions
- Never use ThreadPoolExecutor without a threading.Lock around cache reads/writes in WeatherClient
- Never suggest running Python scripts directly on the ThinkPad — use Discord commands or GitHub

## ALWAYS DO THESE THINGS
- Always read contract rules_primary before evaluating any market
- Always parse settlement station from rules_primary text using parse_settlement_station()
- Always use the correct binary Kelly formula: f* = (p - c) / (1 - c)
- Always enforce the price band: MIN_TRADEABLE_PRICE=0.15, MAX_TRADEABLE_PRICE=0.47
- Always enforce 2x minimum return: profit_if_wins >= stake
- Always enforce minimum bet: MIN_BET_USD=10.0
- Always enforce dynamic position limits: min(POSITION_COUNT_CEILING, floor(0.70 * balance / bet_size))
- Always use IOC (immediate_or_cancel) for order time_in_force
- Always use book_side "bid" for YES buys and "ask" for NO buys in V2 API
- Always apply per-city seasonal sigma from CITY_SIGMA dict
- Always apply per-city NWS bias corrections from CITY_BIAS_CORRECTIONS dict
- Always apply intraday sigma collapse based on hours_until_settlement
- Always run py_compile on all changed files before declaring any fix complete
- Always commit with descriptive messages: "fix:", "feat:", "audit:", "debug:" prefixes
- Always verify fixes with actual test assertions, not just "looks right"
- Always read SKILL.md files before creating any document, presentation, or code file
- Always use PROJECT_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent for all file paths
- Always use load_dotenv(dotenv_path=PROJECT_ROOT / ".env") explicitly
- Always log the settlement station being used for each market evaluation
- Always check for existing open position on same ticker before placing new order
- Always sync real Kalshi balance on bot startup when DRY_RUN=false
- Always use model string "claude-haiku-4-5" for Claude batch calls in claude_checker.py
- Always run calibration_log entry after confirmed fill
- Always update calibration_log with actual outcome after settlement

## KALSHI API RULES
- Base URL: https://api.elections.kalshi.com/trade-api/v2
- Auth: RSA-PSS signing, message = timestamp + METHOD.upper() + /trade-api/v2/path (no query params)
- Orders endpoint: POST /portfolio/events/orders (NOT /portfolio/orders)
- Cancel endpoint: DELETE /portfolio/events/orders/{order_id}
- Order status: GET /portfolio/orders/{order_id}
- Prices: dollar strings ("yes_ask_dollars": "0.3700") NOT integer cents
- Market status field returns "active" for tradeable markets
- Market list query uses status="open" as filter (different from field value)
- Settlement: only finalized + result="yes"/"no" — never infer from price or closed status
- Order format V2:
  {ticker, client_order_id, side: "bid"|"ask", count: "166.00", price: "0.3100",
   time_in_force: "immediate_or_cancel", self_trade_prevention_type: "taker_at_cross"}
- YES buy: side="bid", price=yes_ask_dollars
- NO buy: side="ask", price = 1 - no_ask (YES-leg equivalent)

## CODEBASE STRUCTURE RULES
- discord_launcher.py: the ONLY file that connects to Discord, the ONLY file with bot.run()
- main.py: entry point only, outer restart loop, starts Trader + NWSWatcher
- src/trader.py: full pipeline orchestrator, NO Discord logic
- src/kalshi_client.py: ALL Kalshi API calls, NO business logic
- src/edge_engine.py: ALL signal math, EV calc, price band, NO API calls
- src/weather_client.py: NWS forecasts only, NO Kalshi calls, NO trading logic
- src/metar_tracker.py: METAR real-time observations only
- src/contract_validator.py: validation layer, runs before ANY math evaluation
- src/calibration.py: calibration analytics, NO trading logic
- src/risk_manager.py: SQLite state, position tracking, risk checks
- src/position_sizer.py: Kelly sizing only, NO API calls
- src/claude_checker.py: Claude API calls only, NO weather or Kalshi logic
- src/discord_commander.py: DEPRECATED — do not add code here, do not instantiate
- src/bot_control.py: cross-process trigger files only (scan.trigger, paused.flag)
- data/positions.db: SQLite — single source of truth for all state
- Never create new src/ files without explaining why existing files can't be extended

## ENVIRONMENT & DEPLOYMENT RULES
- ThinkPad venv: /home/astro/WeatherBot/venv/bin/python
- ThinkPad project: /home/astro/WeatherBot
- Windows project: C:\Users\Crazy\OneDrive\Desktop\TradingBot\kalshi-weather-bot
- systemd service: kalshibot.service, managed via discord_launcher.py
- After any code change: git add . && git commit && git push (Windows), then git pull (ThinkPad via Discord or terminal), then !restart
- .env is gitignored — never commit it, never assume its values match .env.example
- Log file: /home/astro/WeatherBot/logs/bot.log
- Database: /home/astro/WeatherBot/data/positions.db
- PID file: /home/astro/WeatherBot/bot.pid (single instance enforcement)

## TRADING RULES (enforce in code)
- Price band: $0.15 - $0.47 only (enforced in _check_price_band)
- Min return: 2x (profit_if_wins >= stake, enforced in size_trade)
- Min bet: $10 USD
- Max bet: $75 USD
- Max bankroll deployment: 70% at any time
- Position ceiling: 6 (dynamic: min(6, floor(0.70*balance/bet_size)))
- Kelly fraction: 0.15
- Settlement window: 36 hours max
- Min EV: 0.05
- Min signal score: 0.75
- Min liquidity: 20 contracts
- NO side bias multiplier: 1.15x on signal score and EV
- Never bet on contracts above $0.47 — violates 2x return rule
- Never bet on contracts below $0.15 — fee drag destroys edge
- Never place more than one bet per ticker per day

## DASHBOARD / FLASK API RULES
- Flask API runs on port 5000 (ATLAS_PORT) alongside the bot
- All API endpoints return JSON: `{ok: bool, data: any, error: str|null, ts: str}`
- Dashboard is React/Vite in `dashboard/` — build with `pnpm build`, served from Flask or Vite dev proxy
- Dashboard polls via `usePoller`: status 15s, positions/balance 30s, metar 5min, logs 60s
- Dark theme only — no light mode
- Never expose API keys or .env values through the Flask API (redact KEY/SECRET/TOKEN/PASSWORD)
- Flask GET endpoints are read-only — no state mutations via GET
- All POST endpoints require `X-Atlas-Secret` header matching `DASHBOARD_SECRET` (hmac.compare_digest, fail closed)
- Frontend sends secret via `VITE_DASHBOARD_SECRET` in `dashboard/.env.local`
- Dashboard must work when bot is stopped — show offline/stale state with BotController fallback controls
- Multi-agent support: each bot registers at `/api/agents/register` on startup (POST with secret)
- See `docs/ATLAS_OVERHAUL.md` for CORS, SSE chat, PID/heartbeat, and JOIN correctness rules

## CALIBRATION LOOP RULES
- Every confirmed fill must create a calibration_log entry immediately
- Every settlement must update the calibration_log entry with actual outcome
- MODEL_VERSION must be bumped in .env after any sigma, bias, or gate change
- Never change more than ONE model parameter between calibration measurements
- !calibration command must always show Brier score, CLV, and top city bias
- !improvemodel must always recommend exactly ONE change, never multiple

## CODE QUALITY RULES
- All new methods must have a docstring explaining purpose, inputs, and outputs
- All exception handlers must log the exception — never silent except: pass
- All Discord commands must be registered with @self.bot.command decorator
- All new config values must be added to both .env.example AND documented in the command that uses them
- All file paths must use pathlib.Path, never string concatenation
- All SQLite connections must use check_same_thread=False
- All API calls must have try/except with appropriate fallback behavior
- All new features must include at least one verification assertion

## COMMUNICATION RULES
- Colt drives all product decisions — implement what is asked, don't redesign without asking
- Do not re-ask for information already established in the session
- Do not request terminal output from the ThinkPad — use !logssince, !gitstatus, !ps instead
- Do not suggest running Python scripts manually on the ThinkPad
- When a fix is complete, show the specific verification output that proves it works
- When something looks wrong, check it rather than defending the existing implementation
- The most expensive mistake in this project was defending a wrong API endpoint — always verify suspicious behavior